chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Government should ensure everyone can get timely, medically necessary care by setting a universal minimum benefit and protecting people from unaffordable out-of-pocket costs, while letting individuals choose among competing public and private coverage options above that floor. It should focus on preventive, primary, mental-health, and rural access, using straightforward eligibility, portable coverage, and strong consumer protections so people aren’t trapped by job or geography. Costs should be contained through negotiated or benchmarked prices, reduced administrative complexity, and payment tied to outcomes and access, with transparent reporting so taxpayers and patients can see results.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Government should guarantee universal access to a clearly defined, affordable core of high-quality care—especially preventive, primary, emergency, and mental-health services—so no one faces medical bankruptcy or avoidable illness. It should use transparent pricing, streamlined enrollment/administration, and outcome-based accountability to control costs and protect taxpayers while supporting provider viability, including in rural and underserved areas. Beyond this public floor, people should be free to choose portable private or employer-based supplemental coverage, with targeted subsidies and community partnerships to expand access and encourage innovation.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Government should ensure everyone has access to an affordable, clearly defined set of essential healthcare services—primary, preventive, emergency, and mental-health care—so no one is denied care or pushed into medical bankruptcy. It should fund this baseline fairly, set strong quality standards, negotiate or regulate unreasonable prices, and simplify enrollment and paperwork to reduce waste while protecting the doctor–patient relationship. People who want more options should be able to choose private supplemental coverage and community-based providers, alongside targeted help for rural areas and vulnerable families, to improve access, outcomes, and long-term fiscal sustainability.
